  "Experiment": "The experimental design consists of three phases: (1) Phantom and Simulated Study, (2) Prospective In Vivo Validation, and (3) Clinical Utility Assessment. In Phase 1, we use brain phantoms and fastMRI-derived simulations to generate multi-contrast datasets (T1w, T2w, PDw, FLAIR) undersampled at R=4, 6, 8 using variable-density Poisson masks. We simulate realistic Rician noise and include synthetic lesions with known contrast behavior to evaluate how the spatial gate responds to anomalies. The untrained U-Net with integrated gate and frequency-channel attention is optimized per subject using AdamW, minimizing a composite loss: k-space data fidelity (range-fixed), perceptual similarity, anatomical coherence (non-local means prior), and contrastive regularization. We perform 100 stochastic forward passes for uncertainty estimation. In Phase 2, we acquire prospectively undersampled data from 20 subjects (including 5 with MS-like lesions) on 3T scanners under IRB approval. Fully sampled references are acquired for comparison. We assess reconstruction quality using NMSE, SSIM, PSNR, and structural similarity index (FSIM). In Phase 3, two neuroradiologists perform blinded visual assessments focusing on lesion detectability, edge sharpness, and uncertainty map interpretability. We compute PICP (Prediction Interval Coverage Probability) and AUUC (Area Under the Uncertainty Curve) to quantify uncertainty calibration. Ablation studies examine the impact of the spatial gate, frequency-channel attention, and dual uncertainty modeling. Comparisons include RNU, DPI, CRONE, and the original team idea. Ideal outcomes: (a) higher SSIM in shared anatomical regions; (b) preserved lesion contrast in FLAIR/T2w; (c) spatially meaningful gate activation patterns; (d) well-calibrated dual uncertainty maps; (e) superior radiologist preference in ambiguous regions.",
